call should get as an argument is the address and the replacement<br />instruction.  So<br /><br />  int text_poke(void *addr, const void *opcode, size_t len)<br /><br />sounds fine to me. And it would do:<br /> - take some (possibly per-mm) mutex<br /> - write the one-byte int3<br /> - do the IPI<br /> - write the other bytes<br /> - do the IPI<br /> - do the first byte<br /> - release the (possibly per-mm) mutex<br /><br />and then in the BP handler we'd just take the mutex, see if the first<br />byte of the exception is still int3, if it's not, just return silently<br />(because that means that we hit the race).<br /><br />And I would seriously suggest just open-coding the above simple<br />sequence instead of trying to force-reuse the text_poke_bp() function<br />we already have. Because I think doing this on kernel code is<br />*very*different* (for irq reasons _and_ for IPI mask reasons).<br /><br />Hmm? It doesn't sound too bad. And I really don't see the point of<br />some timeout handling or anything like that.<br /><br />           Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
